6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 73, L.D. 108, “An Act to Authorize the
10 Release of Military Records to the Office of Chief Medical Examiner for the Purposes of
11 Suicide Reporting and Prevention”
12 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
13 following:
14 'Sec. 1. 37-B MRSA §509, sub-§7 is enacted to read:
15 7. Release of information about military status; suicide reporting and prevention.
16 Upon request by an authorized representative of the Department of the Attorney General,
17 Office of Chief Medical Examiner in the conduct of official duties and with the permission
18 of a deceased person's next of kin, the bureau may release information regarding the
19 deceased person's military service to the Office of Chief Medical Examiner for the purposes
20 of suicide reporting and prevention. If the deceased person has no next of kin, the bureau
21 may release information regarding the deceased person's military service to the Office of
22 Chief Medical Examiner for the purposes of this subsection.'
23 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
24 number to read consecutively.
25 SUMMARY
2266 This amendment, which is the minority report of the committee, replaces the bill. The
2277 amendment provides that the Maine Bureau of Veterans' Services within the Department
2288 of Defense, Veterans and Emergency Management may release information regarding a
2299 deceased person's military service to the Department of the Attorney General, Office of
3300 Chief Medical Examiner for the purposes of suicide reporting and prevention only with
3311 permission of the deceased person's next of kin. The amendment also provides that if the
3322 deceased person has no next of kin, the bureau may release information regarding the
3333 deceased person's military service to the Office of Chief Medical Examiner for purposes of
3344 suicide reporting and prevention.
